04425nam a22007815i 9781442695283DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2017    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426952837 a10.3138/97814426952832doi  a(DE-B1597)479401  a(OCoLC)979911471  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ9108b.V54 2011 7aLIT0042802bisacsh04a869.3/42093582231 aVieira, Patricia, eauthor.10aSeeing Politics Otherwise :bVision in Latin American and Iberian Fiction /cPatricia Vieira. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2011  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Shadows of Vision -- t1. At the Blink of an Eye: Vision, Ethics, and Politics -- t2. Darkness and the Animal in Graciliano Ramos's Memórias do Cárcere (Memoirs of Prison) -- t3. Twists of the Blindfold in Art, Fiction, and Film -- t4. The Reason of Vision: Variations on Subjectivity in José Saramago's Ensaio sobre a Cegueira (Blindness) -- tConclusion Readings in the Dark: Shades of Criticism -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen confronting twentieth-century political oppression and violence, writers and artists in Portugal and South America have often emphasized the complex relationship between freedom and tyranny. In Seeing Politics Otherwise, Patricia Vieira uses an interdisciplinary approach to explore the interrelation of politics and representations of vision and blindness in Latin American and Iberian literature, film, and art.Vieira's discussion focuses on three literary works: Graciliano Ramos's Memoirs of Prison, Ariel Dorfman's Death and the Maiden, and José Saramago's Blindness, with supplemental analyses of sculpture and film by Ana Maria Pacheco, Bruno Barreto, and Marco Bechis. These artists use metaphors of blindness to denounce the totalizing gaze of dictatorial regimes. Rather than equating blindness with deprivation, Vieira argues that shadows, blindfolds, and blindness are necessary elements for re-imagining the political world and re-acquiring a political voice. Seeing Politics Otherwise offers a compelling analysis of vision and its forcible deprivation in the context of art and political protest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aBlindness in literature. 0aLatin American fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin American literaturexPolitical aspects. 0aPortuguese fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442695283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442695283.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG